So that you are able to autowire a bean you need to register that bean as a Spring-managed bean. You can do that in multiple ways, being the following ones the simplest ones:

**1) @Component annotation**

If you annotate `A` with `@Component` Spring will create an instance of the class and register it as a Spring-managed bean:
```java
@Component
Class A {
  B b;
  C c;
//setter based injection
}
```

**2) @Bean annotation**

Another way to register a Bean is using a Configuration class and the `@Bean` annotation:
```java
@Configuration
public class AppConfig {
    @Bean
    public A a() {
        return new A();
    }
}
```

If I understood correctly your use case, you will need to use option 2).

